      <!-- Rest of the prototype is kept verbatim-ish; see marketing/index.html for the full content source. -->
      <section id="tour" class="section">
        <div class="container">
          <h2>Why it’s better than PowerPoint</h2>
          <p class="section-lead">
            PowerPoint is great at slides-as-files. Deckyard is built for slides-as-a-web workflow: faster creation,
            easier publishing, and audience interaction—without giving up control of your data.
          </p>

          <div class="tour">
            <article class="tour-item">
              <div class="tour-visual">
                <div class="visual-frame">
                  <div class="visual-placeholder">Editor (placeholder)</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tour-copy">
                <h3 class="h3-with-icon">
                  <span class="icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true"><svg class="icon"><use href="#icon-rocket-launch"></use></svg></span>
                  Create faster (without pixel pushing)
                </h3>
                <ul class="bullets">
                  <li>Governed slide types = consistent output and easier editing</li>
                  <li>Web-based editor: share a link, not a file</li>
                  <li>Bilingual decks (NL/EN) with per-language presenting and export</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </article>

            <article class="tour-item">
              <div class="tour-visual">
                <div class="visual-frame">
                  <div class="visual-placeholder">Presenter + notes (placeholder)</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tour-copy">
                <h3 class="h3-with-icon">
                  <span class="icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true"><svg class="icon"><use href="#icon-shield-check"></use></svg></span>
                  Present with confidence
                </h3>
                <ul class="bullets">
                  <li>Fullscreen presenting with keyboard navigation</li>
                  <li>Step-by-step reveal for supported slide structures</li>
                  <li>Mobile speaker notes companion (optional remote control)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </article>

            <article class="tour-item">
              <div class="tour-visual">
                <div class="visual-frame">
                  <div class="visual-placeholder">Follow‑along + interactions (placeholder)</div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tour-copy">
                <h3 class="h3-with-icon">
                  <span class="icon-wrap" aria-hidden="true"><svg class="icon"><use href="#icon-globe"></use></svg></span>
                  Built-in interactivity (follow‑along included)
                </h3>
                <ul class="bullets">
                  <li>Follow‑along view for attendees (phone-friendly)</li>
                  <li>Interactions: polls, Likert, feedback, Q&amp;A (where enabled)</li>
                  <li>Designed with lifecycle discipline to keep sessions stable</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="values" class="section section-alt">
        <div class="container">
          <h2>Public values</h2>
          <p class="section-lead">
            The goal isn’t “another slide SaaS”. Deckyard is open source and designed for organizations that need
            control, clarity, and interoperability—without default tracking.
          </p>

          <div class="grid cards">
            <article class="card">
              <div class="card-icon" aria-hidden="true"><svg class="icon"><use href="#icon-globe"></use></svg></div>
              <h3>Digital sovereignty</h3>
              <p>Run it on infrastructure you control. No mandatory cloud dependency.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="card">
              <div class="card-icon" aria-hidden="true"><svg class="icon"><use href="#icon-shield-check"></use></svg></div>
              <h3>Data minimization</h3>
              <p>No third‑party analytics by default. Keep the surface area understandable.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="card">
              <div class="card-icon" aria-hidden="true"><svg class="icon"><use href="#icon-database"></use></svg></div>
              <h3>Operational clarity</h3>
              <p>File-based storage and straightforward backups. Boring ops on purpose.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="card">
              <div class="card-icon" aria-hidden="true"><svg class="icon"><use href="#icon-file-text"></use></svg></div>
              <h3>Accessibility baseline</h3>
              <p>Published decks behave like websites: semantic HTML + keyboard support.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="interop" class="section">
        <div class="container">
          <h2>Interoperability (no lock‑in)</h2>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div>
              <p class="section-lead">
                Your deck shouldn’t be trapped in one platform (or one file format). Deckyard is web-first: publish,
                embed, and export with a portable, readable format—so your work outlives any vendor.
              </p>
              <ul class="bullets">
                <li><strong>Portable deck format</strong> (JSON) for pipelines and future import paths</li>
                <li><strong>Publish links</strong> and an <strong>embed player</strong> for websites/CMS (no “send the .pptx” loop)</li>
                <li><strong>Offline-friendly</strong> HTML export</li>
                <li><strong>Optional AI helpers</strong> (configurable vendors; can be disabled; demo runs without it)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="callout">
              <h3>Works well with</h3>
              <ul class="bullets">
                <li>EU-controlled hosting (VPS / Docker)</li>
                <li>Conference handoff workflows</li>
                <li>Embedding inside CMS, intranet, or project sites</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="fineprint">
                “EU-friendly” means: operator clarity, privacy posture, and optional vendors like Mistral when configured
                — not that hosting is limited to the EU.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="exports" class="section section-alt">
